like we'll need a generic<br />&gt;<br />&gt; CONFIG_RESCTRL<br />&gt;<br />&gt; which should enable the arch-agnostic piece in fs/ and then<br />&gt; the arch-specific counterpart which we'll probably put behind<br />&gt; CONFIG_X86_RESCTRL and CONFIG_ARM64_RESCTRL, respectively.<br />&gt;<br />&gt; I guess I can send you a patch renaming the x86 config option to<br />&gt; X86_RESCTRL and the ARM64 side will fall into place when ready. And<br />&gt; it'll extract the generic bits into that separate generic config option.<br />&gt;<br />&gt; Thoughts?<br /><br />That sounds mostly good to me. Except I still think that<br />"CONFIG_RESCTRL" is too generic, because it's really not about<br />resources in general, it's literally about specific CPU resources.<br /><br />So I'd prefer to call the option for the generic code<br />"CONFIG_CPU_RESCTRL", which is then selected by the arch option (ie<br />CONFIG_{X86,ARM64}_RESCTRL).<br /><br />Anyway, this is mostly bikeshedding, but naming is fairly important.<br />But not time-critical at this point,<br /><br />                 Linus<br /><br /></pre><div align="center"><div class="shariff" data-services="[&quot;reddit&quot;]" data-theme="grey" data-lang="en" data-backend-url="//shariff.lkml.org/index.php"></div></div></td><td width="32" rowspan="2" class="c" valign="top"><img src="/images/icornerr.gif" width="32" height="32" alt="\" /></td></tr><tr><td align="right" valign="bottom">
